After I was administered the first Moderna vaccine at Walgreens, I sat in a chair to wait the recommended 15 minutes. Between 1-3 minutes after, I began to get nauseous and dizzy and then I got a severe headache. I lost control over my body and the papers the nurse had given me slipped out of my hand and the water bottle I was holding fell to the ground. I got extremely hot and started sweating. My mother noticed and alerted the pharmacy I was having a reaction. From what I remember they paged something overhead and I started feeling worse going deep within myself and very removed from the situation. My heart felt abnormal and there was tingling and pain in my head. I could barely communicate and thought I was either dying or was going to have to be wheeled out in a stretcher. Although I couldn't open my eyes or really communicate, I felt the nurse touch me and say I was really hot. She told me to get to the floor. I slid to the floor and someone got a dog bed to put under my head. I started to feel better after about a minute, although I had to just lie there for a few minutes before I could really communicate again.  I then began to get chills and shiver.  They got me water and I asked for a straw because I didn't have the energy to lift my head. I was able to sit up (on the floor still) after about 5 minutes. My mother had called my dad and we waited for him to come to the store so he could help me to the car. has preserved video of the incident. I also have the names of the nurse who treated me, the manager, and the Walgreens pharmacy manager (and my mother who was there) who are all willing to attest to the incident. I felt sick for 9 days - headache, fatigue, nauseous, dizziness (and one episode of diarrhea on the seventh day).  The seventh day was the worst for dizziness and nausea too.  My arm hurt for 5 days.
HISTORY: had drug-induced lupus from minocycline at age 20; had still undiagnosed condition where CRP level was elevated age ~27-28; had different undiagnosed condition from age 30-33 - numerous doctors and specialist could not determine issue and it went away after 7 months of Chinese herbal medicine treatment
ALLERGIES: minocycline, tetracycline, hydroxychloroquine; became allergic/intolerant to nuts and wine at age 30

On April 3, I had a brain hemorrhage. I was doing my normal Saturday morning activities - ate breakfast, did a few simple things around the house, then was doing some light floor exercises. While doing my usual light exercises, I suddenly felt "off" then took a bath. While I was in the bath, I realized that something was wrong with my vision and I had someone take me to the emergency room. I had lost half of my vision as well as experienced significant memory loss, loss of fine and gross motor control, issues with my speech and use of language, unable to do simple math, could not remember or figure out how to use a cell phone, and severe balance and dizziness issues. I spent a week in the hospital, most of that time in the ICU.  After being discharged from the hospital, I needed full-time care for over a month, then still needed a caregiver most of the time for several more months. I started intensive physical, occupational, and speech therapy at a specialized neurotherapy center, which has continued for 6 months.  I have continued to see my neurologist, neuro-ophthalmologist, ophthalmologist, and primary care doctor on a regular basis. They have done numerous tests, including CT scans, MRI scans, MRA scans, vision field tests, tests for my retina and optic nerve, and blood tests. Through all of this testing, they were not able to determine a cause and I have none of the risk factors for having a brain hemorrhage.  I am continuing to do therapy at home, including physical, occupational, speech, and vision therapies. I am not fully recuperated, still not able to work, and the doctors do not know if I will fully recuperate.
LAB_DATA: CT scans, MRI scans, MRA scans, vision field tests, tests for my retina and optic nerve, and blood tests - none resulted in determining a cause of the brain hemorrhage

From H&P: "Patient is a  72 y.o. male who presented to the emergency department due to shortness of breath.  According the patient symptoms started after he was diagnosed with Covid 19 on 9/29.  Reports initially was mild shortness of breath but progressed to severe thus presented to the emergency department for evaluation.  The patient reports symptoms were associated with mild epigastric pain and nausea.  Reports constipation.  Denies chest pain, fever, chills, hemoptysis, lower extremity edema, orthopnea.  Evaluation emergency department included chest x-ray which was negative.  CBC revealed mild leukocytosis with white count 12.7.  Sodium is 131. Lipase was normal.  BNP was normal in trop was negative.  With ambulation the patient required 2 L nasal cannula thus admission was requested.  Upon evaluation patient continues report shortness of breath.  He continues to deny pertinent negatives outlined above.  Does not appear to be in acute distress."   Hospital Course: The patient was admitted to Hospital COVID-19 medical unit for hypoxic respiratory failure secondary to COVID-19 viral pneumonia on 10/04/2021.  He reportedly received the Jansen vaccine, single dose March 2021. Upon admission he was started on dexamethasone, Remdesivir and therapeutic Lovenox.  Patient was diuresed as needed throughout hospital stay and pulmonary was consulted.  Unfortunately the patient continued to have increased oxygen requirements and worsening respiratory distress requiring heated high-flow nasal cannula and was transferred to the ICU on 10/12/2021 and placed on AVAPS.  Patient was started on a Precedex drip for agitation also started on broad-spectrum antibiotics as superimposed bacterial infection cannot be ruled out.    Morning of 10/13/2021 code blue was called, CPR was started immediately and patient was intubated. Several rounds of ACLS were performed and patient was also given bicarb, calcium and dextrose. Unfortunately patient remained asystole or PEA and the code was eventually called. Time of death 0640 October 13th, 2021.    Disposition: Deceased

SYMPTOM_TEXT: CHIEF COMPLAINT/REASON FOR VISIT Chest pressure   HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS Patient is a 71 y.o. man with history of CAD status post LAD stenting in 2013, diabetes mellitus type 1, hypertension, hyperlipidemia on statin therapy, OSA, and medically complicated obesity who I am evaluating in the ED given left elbow discomfort, chest pressure, and abnormal chest CTA.     Patient followed on an outpatient basis with Dr., with most recent evaluation in early 2020 including an exercise stress echocardiogram that was mildly positive for myocardial ischemia in an inferior distribution.  A conservative approach was selected with continued medical therapy, inclusive of 3 antianginals (isosorbide mononitrate, amlodipine, and metoprolol).  Increase in outpatient diuretic was utilized for exertional dyspnea.   Patient tells me that overall he has done well.  He has been outside in the woods ambulating as he prepares for deer and bear hunting season.  He is in the process of moving and earlier today was going up and down a ladder while working in his garage packing and moving boxes.  While doing so, he noticed reduced level of energy.  He has had an intermittent cough but denies fever.  He developed left elbow discomfort that he describes as "heaviness" or an "ache".  Because of this, he went inside and sat down noted that he was diaphoretic.  He noted mild chest pressure.  He took a sublingual nitroglycerin which improved his discomfort.  His wife contacted emergency services and by the time of paramedic arrival his pain had improved but had not completely subsided.  Discomfort resolved in the ambulance and out.  Initially, he was hypotensive.  He denies any dyspnea, palpitations, recent changes in weight, or chills.  He did not experience any chest discomfort or elbow discomfort preceding his prior stent.   On arrival to the ED,  patient receive some fluids given low blood pressure, with resultant normotension.  D-dimer was elevated.  ECG demonstrated no interval changes compared to prior.  CT cardiac angiogram triple rule out was performed (report below).  First troponin was 16.  COVID swab was positive.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: All stages of symptoms that can occur from the vaccine throughout a person's entire body, only occurred in my left arm. About an hour after the shot, the site felt like a wasp sting, and around 1630 EDT a hard lump appeared at the injection site, that grew to about the size of a lemon, then I experienced swelling of the upper arm, pain in the whole arm, heat all over the arm, then chills in the arm, then inability to raise my arm - by evening my arm felt like I had severely injured a rotator cuff or other shoulder muscle, and it felt like it was made of lead (very heavy). These symptoms continued throughout the night, especially the chills, and I couldn't raise my elbow above waist high. This morning, all the symptoms have receded and I only feel moderate ache in my upper arm, but still have some difficulty lifting it.  I tried to find information on the internet about anyone else having experienced a range of symptoms only in the arm of the vaccination, and I haven't found any evidence of that, so I thought it was worth reporting.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Sunday (7/18/21) I went in to get my first dose of the COVID vaccine. Everything was fine until the evening of Wednesday (7/21/21) when I started to feel a tightness in my right Mid back. I didn't think anything of it at the time as it just felt like muscle tightness. The next morning I woke up and could barely get out of bed from the pain. It felt like a knife was in my back. I was able to get up and move around, but it was pretty debilitating as I sat around all day. I figured I slept wrong or a possible rib was out of place. I started to develop shortness of breath and rapid heart rate throughout the day as well. The symptoms got worse throughout the next few days and over the weekend. I pushed through the pain as I naturally have a high pain tolerance being a bigger athletically built guy. On Monday (7/23/21) I started to feel a bit better and thought I was recovering. It wasn't until the next day the pain came roaring back and at that point I knew something was going on. On Wednesday (7/28/21) I coughed up some blood in the morning. I was honestly in shock a bit and figured it was blood in my morning flem as a 'Bloody booger' or something. On Friday (7/30/21) I coughed up a significantly more amount of blood and immediately knew I had to go see my Doctor. I made an appt immediately and went in that morning. After doing some initial tests, my Doctor sat me down and told me he thinks I have a blood clot in my right lung and need to go to the ER immediately to get diagnosed. After being emitted to the ER, all the tests and scans came back positive that a blood clot in my lung was correct. They told me I actually have multiple blood clots in both lungs. I was in utter shock as I have always been a healthy individual. After being in the ER for a couple nights they put me on Eliquis blood thinner right away and have been taking two doses/day ever since. I was released from the ER on Sunday afternoon (8/1/21).
LAB_DATA: Multiple tests were taken that are all in my Hospital reports, which I will include. I am honestly not well versed on the medical language/tests.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I got my first dose of the Moderna vaccine on 2/23/2021. On 3/3/2021, I began developing tingling in the fingers of both hands. It got worse over the next 2 days to the point that the fingers were both burning and tingling. I could only get relief by putting my hands on something really cold, such as a refrigerator shelf. Late on 3/6/2021, the burning and tingling began to improve, and they were almost gone by early 3/7/2021.  Later on 3/7/2021, I developed shortness of breath, weakness, and rapid heart rate. I sent a Kardia tracing to my PCP, who read it on 3/8/2021.  She detected ventricular tachycardia, atrial fibrillation, and atrial flutter, and she had me go to the ER immediately.  On 3/8/2021, I went to the ER. I underwent various blood tests, several EKGs, and various other tests. I was in intensive care for 3 days and was seen by various cardiologists. None of them understood why I developed atrial fibrillation, ventricular tachycardia, and atrial flutter all at the same time.   An ablation was performed to stop the atrial flutter. A pacemaker/ICD was also implanted to control the ventricular tachycardia and atrial fibrillation. I was released on 3/11/2021. I have had no recurring symptoms since then.  I received my second Moderna dose on 3/23/2021. The only side effect I experienced was tenderness at the injection site for a day.
LAB_DATA: I underwent various blood tests and EKGs between 3/8/2021 and 3/11/2021 at hospital. I had atrial flutter, ventricular tachycardia, and atrial fibrillation.
OTHER_MEDS: Metoprolol, Tylenol, ibuprofen, Zyrtec, pseudoephedrine, multivitamins, calcium, fish oil, CoQ10, vitamin C, magnesium, evening primrose oil, aspirin.
PRIOR_VAX: Redness, slight discomfort, fever, headaches from various flu shots.
ALLERGIES: Codeine, Stadol, Demerol, Valium, Tylox, Ativan.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient:  Oct 14, 2021: 59 year old female patient received her second COVID 19 vaccine. Patient stated before the vaccine was administered that she had an allergic asthmatic reaction six hours post vaccination.  Patient spoke to provider and was given medical consent to receive second dose and to bring personal albuterol and epinephrine with her. Patient also stated that she took Benadryl prior to vaccine appointment.  After the vaccine was administered the vaccinator asked the patient how he was feeling and the patient stated he was "fine".  Patient was given discharge instructions and told to sit for thirty minutes in the observation area. It was there that the patient began to at first cough and then began wheezing and gasping for air. Patients vitals were taken and Epi Pen was administered immediately. Rapid response team from the ER was called and provider monitored patient until ER unit responded. Patient did not have albuterol on her person.  Vital signs were as follows HR 129, Spo2 97, A/O x3 BP was unsuccessful. Patient was transferred to the Emergency Room based off hospital protocol.

I went to see the outpatient stat care and they gave me a shot of Benadryl and sent me home. The swelling went down but I developed a rash and some welts on my right shoulder, left hip, and left side. That lasted for about 4 days. One week to the day I woke up early my tongue was swelling and my throat was shutting off. I went to the ER. Benadryl did not help. Epinephrine did not help either. They put me on a ventilator for a short amount of time. Now I take 3 different medications The allergist that I have seen said that I need to take those medications at least for 6 months to make sure I do not have any other adverse events. It took me a long time to recover after being in the hospital. I am sure they did medical tests but I was under anesthesia so I do not remember. I was admitted to ICU for 2 days.

But over the past several months it was becoming less effective. I reached out to my doctor and they said to increase the dosage. And I was also taking Tums for heartburn. That's something I've needed to take in combination to manage. My heartburn has been triggered by stress, and it's been a stressful time. I'm not sure if it's in relation to the vaccine but it's just a really stressful time. With symptoms: heartburn happens regardless of my diet, drinking water causes heart burn, it's a very intense uncontrollable heart burn. May 24, 2021 Audiology HISTORY: Patient reported getting dizziness on 5/8/2021 after receiving her second dose of the covid-19 vaccine. She reported feeling very off balance and had bursts of spinning sensations that were exacerbated with head/body movements. She followed up with urgent care on 5/13/2021 at which time she prescribed meclizine and suspected to have BPPV. Patient stated that her dizziness did not improve and then a week later she had a decrease in hearing in her right ear, right sided tinnitus and loss some of her taste. She followed back up with UC on 5/22/2021, was prescribed prednisone and recommended to follow up with audiology/ENT urgently. Patient states that the prednisone has helped her hearing slightly but it is still not back to 'normal'. She also reports that her taste is better. Her tinnitus has not improved. Patient denied any concerns for her hearing prior to a few weeks ago. She does have a history of PE tubes as a child and recurrent ear infections as an adult. She denied otalgia, history of noise exposure and family history of hearing loss. ASSESSMENT:  Otoscopic inspection revealed clear ear canals, bilaterally. Pure-tone air and bone-conduction testing revealed a mild sloping to moderate sensorineural hearing loss in the right ear and essentially normal hearing in the left ear. Speech reception thresholds were obtained at 20 dB in the right ear and 35 dB in the left ear. This was in good agreement with pure tone thresholds. Word discrimination scores were exellent (96%) in the right ear and excellent (100%) in the left ear.    Test reliability was good.   Tympanometric assessment was conducted due to asymmetric hearing loss. Tympanometric results revealed normal ear canal volume, middle-ear pressure, and TM compliance bilaterally. I did have 'long haul' symptoms for ~1.5 years.

Symptom onset was overnight and patient woke with complaints of left sided weakness. He was seen by teleneurology and CTA showed occlusion at the right ICA origin. CT perfusion scan revealed at risk tissue that was felt to be amenable to reperfusion, so pt was transferred to Hospital emergently for cerebral thrombectomy. He was intubated for procedure. Of note he is Covid positive. Patient was extubated after procedure on 10/1. Patient was reintubated on 10/7. He developed acute hemodynamic instability and worsening hypoxemia on 10/11/2021. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Second TDAP vaccine, last one was in 2010 at 13 years old with no issues. Began itching slightly on neck/hair line about 30 minutes after vaccine administration, but nothing severe. Broke out in hives from top of head to feet around 8:00pm that evening. I took 50mg of  Benadryl with no shortness of breath/airway involvement at that time. About 30 minutes later, my throat began to feel scratchy and full. Face, lips, and eyes also began to swell around this time. I went to the ER around 9PM due to angioedema/periorbital edema and was given decadron PO and pepcid PO. After an hour of eval, the swelling or itching had not changed significantly so the ER MD gave me 25mg IM of atarax. I was monitored for approx. 45-60 more minutes and was released home with no issues and an RX for a steroid pack, pepcid, and hydroxyzine. Rash has completely dissolved at this time with no current issues.
LAB_DATA: O2 monitored while at ER (approx 9PM): 97-100% the entire length of stay BP monitored while at ER ( approx 9PM): WNL HR while at hospital (approx 9PM): WNL No other lab tests performed during stay.
OTHER_MEDS: Levothyroxine 50mcg PO QAM; Women's One-a-day multivitamin

About 10 minutes after the vaccine, the patient's arm went numb and then became painful. Patient got dizzy and had tunnel vision. This resolved after 5 minutes of sitting down. The next morning (Friday, 10/8), patient woke with a bad headache and remained home from school. Tylenol was taken throughout the day. Friday evening, patient complained that it was difficult to breathe and there was a pain in the center of her chest. Patient took 2 puffs of Albuetrol, which did not resolve the symptoms. After 30 minutes, patient took Benadryl. An hour later, breathing was better but patient indicated it felt like her chest was being squeezed. Saturday morning, patient woke with headache and a feeling of the chest being squeezed and not being able to get enough air. Doctor was consulted via phone and advised to give ibuprofen, to use a heating pad on the chest, and to limit activity. Ibuprofen would help with the pressure feeling but would need to be given every 4-5 hours to prevent the feeling. This continued all through Sunday and Monday (patient missed school again). On Tuesday, the patient woke with no headache but still had the uncomfortable pressure (which was slightly better). Patient returned to school after taking ibuprofen. Gradual improvement was seen Wednesday and Thursday. Patient is still taking ibuprofen as the pressure pain comes and goes. Patient indicated that there have been a couple of episodes of her vision getting blurry in school since returning.

Received 9 units platelets and over 3 units PRBC.  Diagnosed with bilateral sub segmental PEs but not candidate for anticoagulation due to bleeding risk. Evidence of rhabdomyolysis  with AKI.  Treated with cefepime and zyvox due to sepsis and shock. Coagulopathy continued with cyanosis of the upper and lower digits. Decreased pulsations in the dorsal pedis and upper extremities.  Ultrasound showed no flow in right dorsalis pedis and dampened flow in right and left ulnar arteries. Given prophylactic anticoagulation due to bleeding risk. Mucosal bleeding increased. A=complicated course with encephalopathy and unable to be weend from vent.  Family aware and transitioned to comfort care.

They immediately asked if I knew about regenerance. It's not available in town at this time. So the doctor's nurse called around and asked if anyone had the infusion and they found a place in (Privacy). I called up there and they confirmed that they had the infusion and I asked if I could get up there to get the infusion. This was late in the afternoon and they set me up an appointment for 4:30pm. On a normal day without commute, I can't get there within an hour normally. But the doctor said he would wait for me and he did. I did not reach his office until after 5pm. And he was there by himself at the time. It took about an hour to infuse, and he kept checking in with me to make sure that I was okay. And then I was able to go home. After that I still continued to have nausea and diarrhea and of course the cough which I still have. My oxygen level was down to 91 when I got to the doctor's office for the infusion. And after he gave me the infusion it was up to 97. And then for about a week afterward, I continued to have nausea and diarrhea. I think the diarrhea was because I only could hold down fluids. I was very tired most of the time and I wanted to sleep most of the day. And that lasted for about a week. I have definitely gotten better throughout the week. And I'm able to stay up during most of the day and sleep through the night. High dose flu vaccine 9/17.

I was flown to another hospital where several tests were performed including MRI etc.  and confirmed again that it was a stroke.   Was released the following day with medication prescribed by doctors.  The fact that I had gotten my first vaccine that morning, was brought up multiple times and was  side stepped.  They told me it wasn't likely that the vaccine is what caused it, but would not rule it out.  No doctors up until today when I had follow up appt, have told me to report this event.

I started getting a major headache. That lasted a couple of days. The second day, I started sweating profusely at night. I had to change my shirt three or four times a night. I had a temperature of 103. I had no congestion. I didn't have any phlegm. It was mainly the headache the and profuse sweating and then I started getting a little achy. That lasted about three days. The fourth day, I went to take a COVID test negative result. I called my personal doctor and told him my symptoms. He thought I might have had COVID. I went to retake the test by his request the following day, it came back negative again. After that, I went to see the doctor about two days after the second test. I was feeling crummy still. He looked at me and he sent me for a chest x-ray and gave me antibiotics, not sure what the antibiotic was. And I took the antibiotic for 10 days. And chest x-ray came back and he said he wanted me to take another one before he told me what was wrong. And he did blood tests, too. I took the second chest x-ray about five days into the antibiotic regimen and by then I had started feeling better. Took the second chest x-ray and two days later, he told me I had a minor case of pneumonia. He said my blood test showed a high, it was reading high that I had a real bad infection. I think about a week and 1/2 later after the antibiotic regimen, I started feeling a lot better. My sweats had almost diminished. My temperature came down to 98 degrees. It took about two weeks where I started feeling a lot better but I wasn't 100% still. I went to the doctor about three weeks after it all started. I told him I felt a lot better and everything seemed normal. I went for a third chest x-ray. He said my chest was fine and to go ahead and finish the regimen of antibiotics. I was good about a month later.
LAB_DATA: Three chest x-rays, blood tests, COVID tests, all ordered by the doctor

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I journalled my symptoms from the moment I got vaccinated. My workplace mandated the vaccine. I will list all my worst symptoms here and go more in detail on the next page.  Chest Pain and Tightness (high d dimer levels); Significant Menstrual Cycle Changes; Extreme fatigue-9/4/21; Chills-9/4/21; Loss of appetite-9/4/21; Severe sudden sharp pain in left ankle-9/7/21; Pain in left knee -9/7/21; Phantom sensation then pain in right arm (non-injected arm); Pain in left shoulder...  I must emphasize that before this, I was a perfectly healthy 25 year old woman. No pre-existing conditions, no pain, not overweight.  Items 18&19:  High D-Dimer levels: I was feeling chest tightness on and off from 9/8/21. This escalated to chest pain on September 15th, to the point where I left work early to go to the ER. I strongly requested the doctor to run a d-dimer test. He told me I needed a CAT scan when he saw the results. They were nearly 3x higher than the top of the normal range for D-Dimer levels. Fortunately, there was no evidence of a pulmonary embolism.   Chest Pain and Chest Tightness: I never experienced this before the vaccine. Started 9/8/21, on and off. Still ongoing.  Significant Menstrual Cycle Changes--I had regular periods before. -Painful sudden cramps, even when I'm not having my period or near having my period -Spotting (I never spotted before) -Early 1-day period: I had a period for one day, September 12th. Way off my cycle. -Period started Sept 29th. For the 29th, 30th, and Oct 1st most of what I was passing were clots. Very large blood clots. On Sept 30th I got up 4 times during the night to change a completely full pad each time.   9/7/21: Sudden, sharp, severe pain in left ankle: I couldn't walk. This came on suddenly with no warning, as I was about to leave for work. On a scale of 1-10, it was easily a 10. This lasted for about 10 minutes, and then went away. Periodically, throughout the day I would feel a level 6 pain on my left ankle, so I would have to limp a bit, but then it would go away. Same day: While I was getting up from sitting down, I would feel pain in my left knee.  9/4/21 (day of vaccination) -Extreme fatigue: started 3:26pm, lasting the rest of the day. It felt like I was moving in slow motion. What normally would take me one hour to cook took me three hours. -Loss of Appetite: I had absolutely no appetite whatsoever. I literally had to force feed myself dinner. And I love food.  -Chills: At 8:00pm, my fingers started feeling very cold. At 8:16pm I had chills all over my body. Needed a warm blanket on top of the layers of clothing I was wearing.  Weird sensation in left arm (injection arm): 9/4/21 tingling and for lack of a better word(s), my entire arm felt strange. My left arm felt very light. I have never had this sensation before.   Phantom sensation/pain in right arm: 9/8/21 I felt the same pain and/or sensation in my right arm, the arm that did NOT receive the injection. It was in the mirror, or "same" location as the left side. At 7:27pm on 9/4/21 (injection day) I also felt pain in my right elbow. That pain went away at 7:30pm.
LAB_DATA: Bloodwork: 9/15/21 & 9/16/21 D-dimer: 9/16/21, nearly 3x higher than the normal range Chest X-Ray: 9/16/21 CAT Scan: 9/16/21
OTHER_MEDS: Multivitamin, Zyrtec, Vitamin D, Zinc, Vitamin C

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Did initial evaluation and patient stated that they did have a fear of needles ever since they were a child.  When asked if they have had any reaction to any previous vaccines like the flu they said no.  The vaccine was administered and the patient went a little pale and kind of fell slightly to the side. Administrator talked to him and he was ok for a few seconds and then he passed out and went in to (what was later determined as) an emotional distress seizure and was non-responsive for about 10-15 seconds.  Patient asked to be laid on the floor so administrator laid him on the floor at that point and was able to get him fully coherent and talking again.  The patient stated that they were slightly nauseas and having trouble moving their hands and had a little trouble speaking.  Administrator offered him some water and patient drank most of the water. Medical personnel arrived within 2 minutes and did an evaluation and determined that he suffered from psychosomatic from his extreme fear of needles and subsequently suffered a minor/short emotional seizure from the stress.  They offered to take him to the hospital for further evaluation if wanted but the medic stated that it was not necessary since it was a reaction to his fear of needles.  Patient decided to stay and not go to the hospital because he was now feeling a lot better.  Medic stated that he was confident that the patient would be just fine and we asked that he stay for at least an hour so we can evaluate for further symptoms.  He had some nutrients and drank some more water after the medical evaluation. No further symptoms were shown.

I ended up in the hospital 6days after my booster, with elevated Troponin levels HOWEVER, THEY FOUND NO DAMAGE to my heart.   I was exhausted the day after my vaccine, 09/21 continuing through the weekend when I started vomiting and became disoriented.  The next day i went to the hospital and upon checking my Troponin levels, they were found to be elevated,  This led the docs to believe I was having a heart attack or a stroke.  I HAVE NEVER HAD A HEART PROBLEM and am in good health.  The did learn I had a UTI, HOWEVER, troponin levels do not elevate with a UTI, and the docs were not worried about my UTI.  They have not been able to find any reason for the elevated Troponin levels.  During this stay in the hospital and these elevated Troponen levels (.20, .28, .29, .21) I had a plethora of tests, all indicating my heart was not damaged... echocardio, 2 EKG's, a brain scan, constant heart monitor machine, and maybe more tests.   Two days after being discharged from the hospital, I had a stress/cardio profusion test and when meeting with the cardiologist and he looking over all of the tests, she said my heart is in excellent condition and shows NO SIGNS OF of any heart damage, or signs of a stroke or heart attack.   There has been nothing found to explain the elevated troponin levels, and now that I'm ~2wks past all of this, my Troponin level is back down to <.02.
LAB_DATA: .20 Troponin1   09/27/21 8:10pm  .28 Troponin1   09/28/21 2am .29 Troponin1   09/28/21 7:45am .21 Troponin1   09/28/21 1:15pm 2 wks later <.02 Troponin1  10/14/21

Hospitalized;  COVID-19 positive (10.6.21);  Fully vaccinated. Admission Date: 10/6/2021 Discharge Date: Oct 9, 2021 PRESENTING PROBLEM: Hyponatremia  Hypophosphatasia  Encephalopathy COVID-19  Acute respiratory failure due to COVID-19  HOSPITAL COURSE: This is a 66-year-old gentleman with a history of progressing right chest mesothelioma, as well as type 2 diabetes mellitus.  He has had some progressive memory problems and word-finding problems over the past months, but developed acute worsening mental status in the 3 days prior to admission.  When he came to the emergency room he was found to have fever and was borderline hypoxemic.  He was found to have COVID-19 infection.  He had anemia with a hemoglobin of 10.4, and subsequent anemia workup revealed an iron saturation of 3% consistent with iron deficiency anemia, as well as of vitamin B12 level of 189 consistent with vitamin B12 deficiency.  He was treated with IV iron sucrose, of which he received 2 doses of 200 mg during his hospital stay.  He was also treated with 1000 mcg of vitamin B12 IM. For his COVID-19 infection he was started on remdesivir and dexamethasone.  He developed acute agitated confusion after admission requiring IV Haldol.  This was thought to be a steroid psychosis, and it resolved with discontinuation of the IV Decadron.  He is on oral Decadron 2 mg daily as an outpatient which was resumed.  He also seemed to develop some confusion from remdesivir dosing so this was stopped as well.  By discharge she was at his baseline mental status.  He was breathing comfortably without oxygen.   For his altered mental status he had a head CT on admission which was negative, and also an MRI of the brain with and without contrast which was normal except for evidence of small-vessel cerebrovascular disease. Discharge medications include the addition of ferrous sulfate 325 mg daily and vitamin B12 500 mcg daily. Follow-up recommendations include consideration Neurology consultation to evaluate cognitive dysfunction.  For his vitamin B12 deficiency and iron deficiency recommend follow-up complete blood count, B12 levels, and iron levels to determine if IM B12 maintenance is necessary or IV iron infusions are necessary.

Started with fingertip pain a week or two after getting second shot. A few weeks to a month after that joint pain in the fingers began to develop. 2-4 weeks after that muscle pain in the arms began to develop. During all of this I was seeing my primary care doctor and trying to diagnose these symptoms and was eventually referred to a rheumatologist, which I filled out in the report as the contact doctor. After running lab tests, he diagnosed me with Lupus (SLE). After starting treatment with hydroxychloroquine I have also developed pain around the chest/lungs when taking a deep breath in, which he said could be inflammation of the muscle lining around it but that has not been confirmed.

Patient is here with wife and daughter due to cough, shortness of breath, decreased appetite.  He is known to have interstitial lung disease, COPD, diastolic heart failure, pulmonary hypertension.  He was hospitalized a little bit over a week ago for similar symptoms.  He was felt to be in heart failure due to an elevated BNP at 503.  He was given IV Lasix but that adversely affected his kidney function.  He was transitioned and discharged to 20 mg of Lasix daily.  He is on chronic oxygen.  Since being at home he has not been doing well.  He has cough productive of clear sputum, shortness of breath and yesterday he had a fever of 100.6.   Yesterday and earlier today when we heard of his difficulties we recommended that he go to the emergency department.  He and his wife absolutely refused.  They are well aware that emergency department is the most rapid and efficient way of getting testing done.  In spite of this they wanted to come into the office to see me today.  Patient arrives in a wheelchair.  He appears to be in moderate respiratory distress.  He appears weak and frail.  I confirmed with patient and his wife their desire to return to the hospital.  They are again very clear that they do not want emergency department evaluation.  They would like for me to do what I can in the outpatient setting. He has been undergoing treatment with dexamethasone and Remdesevir for COVID-19 pneumonia.  He did receive IV Tocilizumab treatment per ID for worsening acute on chronic respiratory failure with hypoxia requiring maxed out high flow nasal cannula oxygen.  He also required empiric antibiotics for possible superimposed community-acquired pneumonia.  Over the past 24 hours he developed worsening acute on chronic respiratory failure with hypoxia requiring maxed out high flow nasal cannula oxygen and nonrebreather. Spoke to ED physician personally and agree with admission.     History of Present Illness     Patient is an 80 y.o. female.       I personally interviewed patient, reviewed chart, and reviewed emergency room resident history and agree with it in its following entirety unless otherwise noted below.  "Patient is a 80 y.o. woman with a history of dementia, HTN, HLD, CKD stage III, hyperparathyroidism, GERD, who reports the emergency department with shortness of breath.  Patient coming from SNF via EMS, is reportedly COVID-19 positive.  This morning was found to be complaining of worsened shortness of breath, found to have room air saturations in the 70 percentile.  Placed on 1 L nasal cannula with improvement to 95%, sent to ED for evaluation and care. Patient currently reports shortness of breath, nonproductive cough. Denies any chest pain, nausea/vomiting, diarrhea, myalgias, headache.    Has received 1 dose of the Pfizer vaccine.   80 y.o. woman with a history of dementia, HTN, HLD, CKD stage III, hyperparathyroidism, GERD, who reports the ED via EMS from SNF with shortness of breath and hypoxia in the setting of COVID19 infection.  HPI as per below.  Afebrile, tachypneic in the mid 20s with an SPO2 95% on 3 L nasal cannula, hemodynamically stable.  Physical exam shows well-appearing elderly woman in NAD, heart regular no M/R/G, lungs with faint crackles in all lung fields, abdomen soft and ND/NT, mucous membranes are moist, no significant lower extremity edema.  Differential diagnosis includes likely worsening COVID-19 infection, possible superimposed bacterial pneumonia, lower concern for PE or ACS given lack of chest pain or other significant symptoms.  Will obtain CBC, CMP, lactate, Covid inflammatory markers, RVP, EKG, CXR.  Will give 6 mg Decadron IV for hypoxia in the setting of COVID-19.  Anticipate hospitalization given degree of hypoxia and new supplemental O2 requirement.   Per POLST, patient is FULL CODE."   On my bedside evaluation she is resting on 3 L nasal cannula and is relatively comfortable appearing but she is a very poor historian.  Does not note any pain or edema in her legs.  No belly or chest pain.  She does feel like she is getting enough air at this time

In the emergency room patient found her saturation 89% on room air, having fever 100.5, x-ray of the chest showed bilateral infiltrates, lab work showed AKI on CKD. Covid test came back positive, patient also admission for hypoxia due to COVID-19 pneumonia.   Patient seen examined bedside, not in acute distress, comfortably resting in the bed Hospital Course:   Please refer to the admission H&P for details of presentation. In summary, Patient with known history of hypertension, dyslipidemia & peripheral vascular disease with admitted to the hospital service for evaluation of cough and fever.  Patient was found to be having hypoxia secondary to bilateral COVID-19 pneumonia and subsequently was treated with remdesivir and Decadron.  Patient completed the course of remdesivir during hospitalization.  Patient had acute kidney injury that improved with IV hydration.  Patient had mild bradycardia during hospitalization while on remdesivir.  Patient also had elevated lactic acid which improved during hospitalization.  Patient had positive blood cultures upon admission which was coagulase-negative staphylococcus, thought to be contaminant.  His blood culture is well controlled during hospitalization hydrochlorothiazide was stopped and the dose of lisinopril was reduced to 20 mg once daily at discharge.  Patient currently feels well and is wanting to go home today.  Patient is advised to follow-up with primary care physician within a span of one to 2 weeks. History of Present Illness     Pt is an 50 y.o. female who presented to the ED with worsening cough and shortness of breath.  Patient has a past medical history of COPD on home O2, atrial fibrillation, pulmonary hypertension, diastolic heart failure, hypertension, anxiety/depression, type 2 diabetes.  She has chronic hypoxic respiratory failure from COPD, using 3 LPM of O2 at home.  Her symptoms started 6 days ago.  She had worsening cough compared to her baseline.  She also had worsening shortness of breath at rest and on exertion.  She has chronic bilateral leg swelling that is also worse.  She has had poor appetite.  No diarrhea or abdominal pain.  She also complains of intermittent chest pain which is usual for her.  She was diagnosed with COVID-19 on October 5, 2021 at an urgent care center.  She had an x-ray done at urgent care which showed multifocal pneumonia.  She was advised to go to the hospital but she did not want to.  She has persistent symptoms so she eventually went to the emergency department.    Patient received only 1 dose of Pfizer vaccine in January 2021.  She states that she did not receive the second dose because she thought that she had a reaction to the first dose -she claims that she had more coughing and dyspnea after first dose.     At the ED, patient was tachypneic with RR 24, she was requiring 4 LPM of O2 at the ED.  D-dimer was elevated 0.79.  CTA of the chest is negative for PE.  There is diffuse interstitial disease with mild groundglass opacity of the right lung apex that is nonspecific.  Lactic acid was 2.5.  Patient was given NS bolus 1 L at the ED.   Patient will be admitted for treatment of acute on chronic hypoxic respiratory failure secondary to COVID-19 pneumonia.  She is at high risk for deterioration given COPD and heart disease. SYMPTOM_TEXT: The moment I received my first covid vaccine it hurt my arm terribly and I could barely use my arm for the first 3 days and had a lot of pain from the injection site all the way down my arm to my elbow for next 8 days. Over the next 3 months I could point to the exact place the injection was administered and felt intermittent muscle pain from the injection site down to my elbow. It gradually got worse and worse until mid-June when my shoulder began to move around and pop and felt like it was almost dislocating. This began by simply raising my arm above my head. Ever since then my shoulder joint continues to move and pop and the muscles all the way down my arm to my elbow hurt almost constantly and sometimes extreme pain.  I can still point to the exact spot of the injection site and my shoulder continues to move and pop and makes my muscles all the way down my arm to my elbow feel pulled very badly and in addition, the muscle at the top of my shoulder that connects to my upper chest, right at the front of my armpit, is very, very tight and I sometimes now have muscle pain all across my chest and my upper back feels compromised now as well.  This is now 7 months since my first injection and I am still in a lot of pain and sometimes cannot use my arm.  The 2nd Pfizer Covid shot was administered on 3/26/2021 in my right arm and once I told them all the trouble I was having after the first shot, they used a smaller needle and made sure to place it in the right spot.  I have had no problem with the right arm.  It seems to me that the first shot was placed either too high or too deep.  I seem to also be having an inflammation reaction to stress in all the areas described in my left arm so am wondering if the Covid vaccine has caused all this or if it was the placement of the vaccine.  I have been in physical and massage therapy since mid-June, so in therapy once a week now for over 3 months.  I have a little better mobility in my right arm but am still experiencing all the pain and movement in my shoulder daily.  For 4 months there has never been a day my arm does not hurt and for 3 months prior to that, I had intermittent pain weekly.  I feel I am about to have to go to an Orthopedist and certainly hope this vaccine has not caused me to have to have surgery or permanent damage to my left arm muscles, ligaments, or tendons.

The patient received concomitant medications in two weeks which included levothyroxine sodium (SYNTHROID) and multivitamins (VITAMINS NOS). No other vaccine in four weeks. No COVID prior vaccination and not tested COVID post vaccination. The patient historical vaccine included received first dose of bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE, solution for injection, Lot Number: EN6062), via an unspecified route of administration, administered in arm left on 13Mar2021 (at the age of 31-year-old) as dose 1, single for COVID-19 immunization and experienced delayed hypersensitivity reaction in left arm a week after vaccination, red, swollen, itchy, and warm bump at and around inoculation site, induced period and resulted in longer bleeding time and increased amount of blood. As the months progressed, so did the patient injuries. She had to stop cheerleading in 2013 due to her severe symptoms. The patient continued to have trouble keeping up with classes in school. She was at risk of failing almost all of her subjects despite being enrolled in an individualized education program (IEP) in 2014 and also receiving private tutoring. The patient was unable to complete a specialized trade program after completing high school due to the physical and cognitive impairments caused by her quadrivalent human papillomavirus (types 6,11,16,18) recomb. vaccine (GARDASIL)-induced injuries, and thus has put her career dreams on hold. Based upon her chronic and severe post- quadrivalent human papillomavirus (types 6,11,16,18) recomb. vaccine (GARDASIL) symptoms and adverse events as outlined above, and the tests performed by her medical providers, the patient had been diagnosed with various medical conditions, including but not limited to, postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome ("POTS"), orthostatic intolerance ("OI"), fibromyalgia, autonomic dysfunction, migraines, and chronic fatigue syndrome ("CFS"), ovarian cysts, narcolepsy, and pilonidal cysts. The patient also had a substantial fear of suffering additional and ongoing harms, including but not limited to now being at an increased risk of cancer and future symptoms and harms associated with her autoimmune disease and other injuries caused by quadrivalent human papillomavirus (types 6,11,16,18) recomb. vaccine (GARDASIL). As a direct and proximate result of her quadrivalent human papillomavirus (types 6,11,16,18) recomb. vaccine (GARDASIL)-induced injuries, the patient had suffered and continued to suffer economic losses, including considerable financial expenses for medical care and treatment, and diminished income capacity, and she would continue to incur these losses and expenses in the future. Scleroderma; barely move; It was awful; Stabbing pain at bottoms of feet, and inner wrists; Cat scratch infection and tick infections; Cat scratch infection; Suffering for quite awhile; It was quite disturbing and scary; It was quite disturbing and scary; Other pain; feel as though it messed up my immune system as well; get sick much more often; Stabbing pain at bottoms of feet, and inner wrists/ left shoulder pain; I am drained; Excruciating head pain; Case reference number US-BN-2021-002328 is a spontaneous case report initially received from a consumer via GSK (reference number unknown) on 07-Oct-2021, and concerns a patient of an unknown age.  The patient's medical history included headaches, approximately once every few years.  The patient's concomitant medication details were not provided.  On an unspecified day, approximately six years ago, the patient received the first dose of rabies vaccine (brand name unknown, Batch no. was not provided) at an unknown dose and route of administration, for an unknown indication.   On the same day, the patient experienced excruciating head pain (stabbing in one specific area, in back left lower side) which occurred a few hours after the shots. The patient called an emergency room and they said they could not evaluate the patient over the phone. The patient could barely move and was feeling awful. It was reported that it did go away after several hours. The patient also experienced stabbing pain at the bottoms of feet and inner wrists.   On an unspecified date, the patient had few more shots to receive but just one dose at a time, rather than several at once, as reported. The patient was still getting headaches and other pain, but it had improved. The patient also had left shoulder pain, all ice pick type stabbing for a few months. The patient had on and off pain, but not as intense. Before that, the patient barely had headaches, maybe once every few years. The patient was feeling better and ended up getting a cat scratch infection and in addition to other symptoms, all of the past pain came back, with full force and had continued ever since. The patient did not get it as often as used to, but it still was happening in the same areas and regularly though it may not be relentless for hours at a time anymore, but sporadic throughout the day. That pain was different than any typical headache or other pain the patient have had in life. The patient also had issues with tick infections. Since then, but with antibiotics (unspecified), all symptoms improved, except the pain that originated the same day as the rabies shots. Stabbing head pain also happened in same exact area.   The patient had no doubt the shot caused or triggered that. It seemed to came back when the patient's immunity was low or humidity, but it caused the patient a lot of suffering for quite awhile. It was quite disturbing and scary when it first happened, however the patient got used to it, but was drained. The patient felt as though it messed up immune system as well, since the patient got sick much more often, too. Also, what should had been infections that went away with antibiotics, went into years of treatment.   On an unspecified date, the patient had a test that showed nucleolar type cells, that may be linked to scleroderma. The patient went to rheumatologist at the beginning of the problems, but it could take years to diagnose an autoimmune disorder and they sent the patient to a neurologist. It was all years ago, as reported.  The reporter did not provide the seriousness and causality assessment, however it was noted that although the patient was not sure what the vaccine caused, the patient had very limited issues before it. Never had chronic, stabling pain and often headaches. The event of scleroderma was assessed as serious due to it's medical significance.  No further information was provided.; Reporter's Comments: Headache, arthralgia and asthenia are listed for Rabipur according to the Global Datasheet and USPI, whilst feeling abnormal, movement disorder, pain in extremity, pain, cat scratch, infection, immune system disorder, emotional distress, emotional disorder, fear, illness and scleroderma are unlisted for Rabipur according to the Global Datasheet and USPI. Reportedly, on an unspecified day, approximately six years ago, the patient received the first dose of rabies vaccine at an unknown dose and route of administration, for an unknown indication. On the same day, the patient experienced headache, feeling abnormal, movement disorder, pain in extremity and arthralgia (stabbing pain at the bottoms of feet and inner wrists). Later, on an unspecified date the patient developed arthralgia (left shoulder pain), pain, cat scratch and infection. Then the patient had issues with tick infection and since then, but with antibiotics (unspecified), all symptoms improved, except the pain that originated the same day as the rabies shot. Then, as reported, the patient developed the events of immune system disorder, emotional distress, emotional disorder, fear, asthenia and illness. Later, on an unspecified date, the patient had a test that showed nucleolar type cells, that may be linked to scleroderma. The patient's medical history included headaches. The patient's concomitant medication details were not provided. Due to suggestive temporal relationship and since contributory role of the suspect vaccine cannot be excluded, the causality for the events of headache, feeling abnormal, movement disorder, pain in extremity and arthralgia is assessed as possibly related. The causality for all the other events is assessed as unlikely at the moment, due to missing information and not having a clear temporal relationship between the administration of rabies vaccine and the development of the events. This case is considered serious due to medical significance.; Sender's Comments: Headache, arthralgia and asthenia are listed for Rabipur according to the Global Datasheet and USPI, whilst feeling abnormal, movement disorder, pain in extremity, pain, cat scratch, infection, immune system disorder, emotional distress, emotional disorder, fear, illness and scleroderma are unlisted for Rabipur according to the Global Datasheet and USPI. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Nerve damage to hands, legs; Unable to walk; Allergic reaction to anthrax shot; On 26SEP2021, a spontaneous report was received from a company representative who provided information discovered on a social media website.   The reporter provided a video found on an online social media source which discussed a female of an unknown age that received BioThrax (anthrax vaccine adsorbed) on an unknown date and experienced an allergic reaction to the anthrax shot (PT: Drug hypersensitivity) causing disability due to nerve damage to her hands and legs (PT: Nerve injury) and an inability to walk (PT: Gait inability). The patient is seen on the video as being in a wheelchair. The reporter attributes the patient's allergic reaction, nerve damage, inability to walk and resulting disability as related to the anthrax shot. The outcome of the events were not reported.  The patient's medical history and concomitant medication use was not reported.   No additional information was available.  Company Comment:  The Company considers that it is possible that the patient had an allergic reaction as hypersensitivity as it is a known phenomenon that could occur with BioThrax; therefore assessed as "Possible". The assumption that the allergic reaction caused nerve damage to the legs and hands so severe that caused permanent disability is not possible to assess or confirm. It is not know that an allergic reaction could cause neuropathy and although other form of neuropathy like Bell's palsy, has been attributed to COVID 19 and influenza vaccine, it has not been associated to BioThrax nor general neuropathy; therefore, the nerve damage and the inability to walk are considered "Unassessable". More information will be sought.; Sender's Comments: The Company considers that it is possible that the patient had an allergic reaction as hypersensitivity as it is a known phenomenon that could occur with BioThrax; therefore assessed as "Possible". experienced shingles/Suspected vaccination failure; Shingles; rash on side of the body, face, along nerve path; Blisters; Scabs; Pain; Itching; Tingling; Numbness; Fever; Headache; Not feeling well; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Shingrix. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), shingles, rash, blister, scab, pain, pruritus, tingling, numbness, fever, headache and feeling unwell. Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported by patients wife. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient experienced all symptoms listed except gastrointestinal issues. The listed symptoms were as follows: Shingles typically produces a painful rash that blisters and scabs over in 7 to 10 days and clears up within 2 to 4 weeks. The reporter stated that 1 to 5 days before the rash appears, people might experience pain, itching, tingling, or numbness in the area where the rash would develop. Other symptoms at this time could include fever, headache, and a sense of not feeling well. The rash usually erupts in a single stripe on either the left or right side of the body, or sometimes the face, along a nerve path. The reporter stated that it could develop on the arm, thigh, head and even the ear or eye. It was most common on the chest and abdomen. This case was considered as suspected vaccination failure, since the details regarding the completion of the primary immunization, time to onset for event and laboratory confirmation of shingles were not provided. The follow-up would not possible as contact information not available.

Extreme weakness; pins and needles tingling sensation in both hands; Increased heartrate; tightness between the neck and both shoulders; warm sensation around the spinal cord/ warm feeling has now progressed to both legs; fatigue; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of weakness in a 45-year-old female patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Fluarix Quadrivalent 2021-2022 season) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included flu seasonal qiv dresden pre-filled syringe device (Fluarix Tetra Pre-Filled Syringe Device) injection syringe for prophylaxis.   On 6th October 2021 11:00, the patient received Fluarix Quadrivalent 2021-2022 season. On 6th October 2021, the patient started Fluarix Tetra Pre-Filled Syringe Device. On 6th October 2021 19:30, 8 hrs 30 min after receiving Fluarix Quadrivalent 2021-2022 season and Fluarix Tetra Pre-Filled Syringe Device, the patient experienced weakness, pins and needles, heart rate increased, muscle tightness, feeling of warmth and fatigue. On an unknown date, the outcome of the weakness, pins and needles, heart rate increased, muscle tightness, feeling of warmth and fatigue were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the weakness, pins and needles, heart rate increased, muscle tightness, feeling of warmth and fatigue to be related to Fluarix Quadrivalent 2021-2022 season and Fluarix Tetra Pre-Filled Syringe Device.   This report is made by GSK without prejudice and does not imply any admission or liability for the incident or its consequences.   Additional details were reported as follows: The case was reported by the patient. The patient received Fluarix on 6th October 2021, at approximately 11 am, the patient beginning to experience symptoms at approximately 7:30 pm, on the same day.  The patient first experienced a pins and needles tingling sensation in both hands, next experienced an increased heartrate, developing a warm sensation around the spinal cord.  The patient also experienced extreme weakness that was beyond what they would consider normal fatigue.  The patient also developing a tightness between the neck and both shoulders.  The warm feeling had now progressed to both legs, which began early on the day of reporting on 7th October 2021. Pain; where she received the shot, has a hard knot with pain and was feeling hot.; where she received the shot, has a hard knot with pain and was feeling hot.; has hard knot; where she received the shot, has a hard knot with pain and was feeling hot.; left arm, on the outer area, wasred,; Warm to touch/like it had fever; whole arm is swollen; first dose was administered August of last year/2nd dose on 29th Sep 2021; This case was reported by a physician via call center representative and described the occurrence of extensive swelling of vaccinated limb in a 17-year-old female patient who received Men B NVS (Bexsero) (batch number ABXB35AA, expiry date 31st July 2022) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included meningococcal B recom vaccine + aloh + omv pre-filled syringe device (Bexsero Pre-Filled Syringe Device) injection syringe for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included Bexsero (1st dose received in August 2020).   On 29th September 2021, the patient received the 2nd dose of Bexsero and Bexsero Pre-Filled Syringe Device. On 29th September 2021, unknown after receiving Bexsero and Bexsero Pre-Filled Syringe Device, the patient experienced drug dose administration interval too long. On 5th October 2021, the patient experienced extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, erythema of extremities and feeling of warmth. On 6th October 2021, the patient experienced injection site pain, injection site nodule, injection site induration and injection site warmth. On an unknown date, the patient experienced pain. The patient was treated with ibuprofen. On an unknown date, the outcome of the extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site pain, injection site nodule, injection site induration, injection site warmth and pain were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the erythema of extremities was recovering/resolving and the outcome of the feeling of warmth and drug dose administration interval too long were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site pain, injection site nodule, injection site induration, injection site warmth, pain, erythema of extremities and feeling of warmth to be related to Bexsero and Bexsero Pre-Filled Syringe Device.   This report is made by GSK without prejudice and does not imply any admission or liability for the incident or its consequences.   Additional details were provided as follows: The reporter stated that, the patient received a 2nd dose of Bexsero on 29th September 2021, later than the recommended interval which led to lengthening of the vaccine schedule. The patient experienced pain 2 to 3 days after receiving the vaccine.  Tuesday night, on 5th October 2021, it was bad, the patient whole left arm, on the outer area, was kind of looking red, swollen (extensive swelling of vaccinated limb), and warm to touch, like it had fever.  The patient called yesterday on 6th October 2021 and the redness was not there, but the lower part of the left arm was pink, and where she received the shot, has a hard knot with pain and was feeling hot. The patient was coming back today on 7th October 2021 for a follow up, and physician told her to take Ibuprofen.  The reporter asked, should she tell the patient that this was a just a local reaction. The reporter was concerned with the length of time of the reactions.  The reporter stated that, she usually sees reactions within 48 hours after the vaccine, but for this patient was worse on day 6.  The reporter consented to follow up via email.
